<h3>Practical tips for the beginning</h3>
						<ul>
							<li>Prepare to quit smoking
								<ul>
									<li>Write down your reasons for quitting</li>
									<li>Think about the pros and cons of quitting smoking and
										look at this list when you have a craving.</li>
								</ul>

							</li>
							<li>Tell people about your plan to quit smoking. Friends and
								family can offer support.</li>
							<li>Contact a GP, pharmacist or stop smoking advisor for
								advice on the best quit method for you.</li>
							<li>Talk to an ex-smoker. If they can do it so can you.</li>
							<li>Plan to keep your quit day as stress-free as you can.
								Lots of smokers try and give up a few times before they quit for
								good.</li>
							<li>Think about any times you've given up in the past - what
								did you learn?</li>
							<li>Change your routine</li>
							<li>Make your home and car smoke free</li>
							<li>Learn to deal with cravings using the 4d's:
								<ul>
									<li><b>D</b>elay at least 3-5minutes and the urge will
										pass</li>
									<li><b>D</b>eep breathe, slowly</li>
									<li><b>D</b>rink a glass of water</li>
									<li><b>D</b>istract yourself-call a friend, go for a walk.</li>
								</ul>
							</li>
						</ul>

						<h3>Practical tips to remain smoke-free</h3>
						<ul>
							<li>Take one day at time</li>
							<li>Stay positive -look at your pros and cons list and
								remember how far you have come</li>
							<li>Reward yourself-Use the money you have saved by quitting
								to reward yourself</li>
						</ul>